Abstract 
15 
 
16 
Diabetes mellitus is one of the major risk factors for cognitive dysfunction. The pathogenesis of 
17 
brain impairment caused by chronic hyperglycemia is complex and includes mitochondrial 
18 
dysfunction, neuroinflammation, neurotransmitters’ alteration and vascular disease, which lead to 
19 
cognitive impairment, neurodegeneration, loss of synaptic plasticity, brain aging and dementia. 
20 
Glucagon-like peptide-1 (GLP-1), a gut released hormone, is attracting attention as a possible link 
21 
between metabolic and brain impairment. Several studies have shown the influence of GPL-1 on 
22 
neuronal functions such as thermogenesis, blood pressure control, neurogenesis, neurodegeneration, 
23 
retinal repair, and energy homeostasis. Moreover, modulation of GLP-1 activity can influence 
24 
amyloid β peptide aggregation in Alzheimer’s disease (AD) and dopamine levels in Parkinson’s 
25 
disease (PD).  
26 
GLP-1 receptor agonists (GLP-1RAs) showed beneficial actions on brain ischemia in animal 
27 
models, such as the reduction of cerebral infarct area and the improvement of neurological deficit, 
28 
acting mainly through inhibition of oxidative stress, inflammation and apoptosis. They might also 
29 
exert a beneficial effect on the cognitive impairment induced by diabetes or obesity improving 
30 
learning and memory by modulating synaptic plasticity. Moreover, GLP-1RAs reduced 
31 
hippocampal neurodegeneration. Besides this, there are growing evidences on neuroprotective 
32 
effects of these agonists in animal models of neurodegenerative diseases, regardless of diabetes. In 
33 
PD animal models, GPL-1RAs were able to protect motor activity and dopaminergic neurons 
34 
whereas in AD models, they seemed to improve nearly all neuropathological features and cognitive 
35 
functions.  
36 
Although further clinical studies of GPL-1RAs in humans are needed, they seem to be a promising 
37 
therapy for diabetes-associated cognitive decline. 
38 
 
39 
 
40 
1. 
Introduction 
41 
 
42 
The concern for neurodegeneration, a worldwide expanding set of diseases, stimulated the research 
43 
on risk factors related to the lifestyle of the population, leading to interesting findings on the 
44 
association between dysmetabolism and brain impairment. In this perspective, gut/brain axis and 
45 
altered insulin release and response seem to be the main actors in establishing the pathological 
46 
metabolic set up for the development of neurodegenerative diseases. Indeed, insulin works as pro-
47 
Provisional
survival neurotrophic factor with its receptor widespread in cognitive areas as hippocampus and in 
48 
dopaminergic system (Haas et al., 2016; Fiory et al., 2019).  
49 
In the last years particular attention has been devoted to unravel the role of Glucagon-Like Peptide-
50 
1 (GLP-1), a gut released hormone that not only is one of the major components of the gut/brain 
51 
axis, but it is also able to protect pancreatic beta-cells from apoptosis and to induce insulin secretion 
52 
(Cabou and Burcelin, 2011). 
53 
GLP-1 is an endogenous peptide hormone released by intestinal L-cells in response to meal. Gene 
54 
expression generates pro-glucagon (PG), which is processed by prohormone convertases (PC1/3) to 
55 
release the GLP-1 (1–37) peptide precursor (Sandoval and D'Alessio, 2015). Proteolytic cleavage 
56 
and amidation of the precursor protein GLP-1(1–37) generate two GLP-1 active forms with the 
57 
same biological activity namely GLP-1(7–37) and the amidated GLP-1(7–36). GLP-1 is degraded 
58 
by a dipeptidyl-peptidase IV (DPP IV), a serine aminopeptidase expressed in the different organ, 
59 
such as liver, pancreas, gut and brain (Hopsu-Havu and Glenner, 1966; Smith et al., 2019). GLP-1 
60 
stimulates insulin secretion from the pancreatic beta-cells under hyperglycemic conditions and 
61 
reduces glucagon secretion from the alfa-cells recovering insulin sensitivity and enhancing 
62 
glycemic homeostasis (Meloni et al., 2013; Katsurada and Yada, 2016).  
63 
GPL-1 signal transduction is mediated by GLP-1 receptor (GLP-1R), a G-protein coupled receptor, 
64 
leading to cyclic adenosine monophosphate (cAMP) dependent activation of Protein kinase A 
65 
(PKA) and of cAMP-regulated guanine nucleotide exchange factor (Epac). The activation of Epac 
66 
and PKA potentiates in a synergistic way the insulin release from the beta-pancreatic cells through 
67 
phosporylation of the SNARE-associated protein Snapin and activation of L-type voltage gated 
68 
calcium channels (Song et al., 2011). 
69 
It is noteworthy that GPL-1R may operate signal transduction even by activating the PI3K/AKT 
70 
axis as observed in GLP-1 protection against apoptosis with the regulation of CREB and protein 
71 
survival factors like Bcl-2 and Bcl-XL, through the action of β-arrestin-1 and the phosphorylation 
72 
of ERK1/2. Furthermore, the activation of the PI3K/AKT axis can induce the inhibition of specific 
73 
caspases and of NF-κB, with the resulting inhibition of the release of pro-inflammatory cytokines 
74 
(Farilla et al., 2003; Athauda and Foltynie, 2016; Tramutola et al., 2017; Yang et al., 2018).  
75 
Plasticity of GLP-1 action at molecular level is mirrored also in different tissues like the cardiac 
76 
compartment and the brain. GLP-1 plays a pivotal role preventing cardiovascular disorders, which 
77 
makes GLP-1 and its analogs a great resource in the treatment of these diseases (Pozo et al., 2019). 
78 
GLP-1 is also involved in the reduction of the oxidative stress, in the regulation of autophagy and in 
79 
the modulation of central nervous system (CNS) pathways with protective functions and elicitation 
80 
of anti-inflammatory signaling (Li et al., 2009). 
81 
 
82 
2. 
Multifunctional role of GLP-1 
83 
 
84 
GLP-1 is produced at neuronal level of the solitary tract within the brainstem. In addition, this 
85 
peptide, released from the gut, activates the GLP-1R located on vagal sensory neurons that 
86 
constitute the hepato-portal glucose sensor, communicating with brainstem neurons, extending its 
87 
action to different brain regions. Several studies have shown the influence of GLP-1 on neuronal 
88 
function such as thermogenesis, blood pressure control, neurogenesis, neurodegeneration, retinal 
89 
repair, and energy homeostasis (Katsurada and Yada, 2016). Since GLP-1Rs are expressed in 
90 
different brain regions, GLP-1 behaves as a neuropeptide, involved in different peculiar effects 
91 
including the control of satiety, water intake and stress reaction (van Dijk and Thiele, 1999; Meier 
92 
et al., 2002). Kinzig et al. reported that GLP-1-stimulated brain GLP-1Rs are mediator of multiple 
93 
stress responses. GLP-1 administration directly into the rat brain, increases anxiety level, associated 
94 
with a higher production of stress-activated hormones ACTH and corticosterone, demonstrating that 
95 
GLP-1 is able to stimulate at the same time a response by both amygdala and by the paraventricular 
96 
nucleus of the hypothalamus (Kinzig et al., 2003). The increase of GLP-1 in the circulation could 
97 
reach the brain and regulate food intake (Ruttimann et al., 2009). Recent studies showed that GLP-1 
98 
Provisional
in combination with dexamethasone (GLP-1/Dexa) can decrease food intake and lower body weight 
99 
in obese mice without inducing mood or memory deficits (Decarie-Spain et al., 2019). In type 2 
100 
diabetes (T2D), alteration of insulin sensitivity and disturbances of neurogenesis are correlated with 
101 
a reduction in GLP-1 levels in response to food, and its signaling activity (Nauck et al., 2011). 
102 
Recently, several groups reported that GLP-1 contributes to the regulation of neurologic and 
103 
cognitive functions (Muscogiuri et al., 2017). Indeed, GLP-1 is also involved in the control of the 
104 
synaptic plasticity and in some forms of neuroprotection and thus has a regulative role in various 
105 
signaling pathways associated with learning, memory and other synaptic function (Gault and 
106 
Holscher, 2008; Yildirim Simsir et al., 2018). 
107 
 
108 
3. 
Glucagon-Like Peptide-1 Receptor Agonists (GLP-1RAs) as neuroprotective agents in 
109 
diabetes-associated cognitive impairment  
110 
 
111 
T2D is a chronic disease with an increasing global prevalence. Besides the well-known micro- and 
112 
macro-vascular complications, cognitive decline is thought to be an emerging consequence of 
113 
diabetes (Koekkoek et al., 2015). 
114 
Over the last decade GLP-1RAs have emerged as effective glucose-lowering drugs. Exenatide was 
115 
the first GLP-1RA approved for the treatment of T2D. It is a synthetic form of exendin-4, a natural 
116 
GLP-1-like peptide extracted from the saliva of the lizard Heloderma suspectum. Exenatide shares 
117 
53% homology with native GLP-1. Exenatide has a half-life of 2.4 h, whereas GLP-1 has a half-life 
118 
of 2 min. Lixisenatide is based on the structure of exendin-4 has a half-life of 3 h. Liraglutide was 
119 
the first GLP-1RA deriving from native GLP-1, sharing 97% homology and with a half-life of 13 h 
120 
(Aroda, 2018). Semaglutide, a modified form of liraglutide has a half-life is of ~7 days due to a 5.6 
121 
times higher affinity with albumin than liraglutide (Gomez-Peralta and Abreu, 2019). 
122 
Several studies have investigated the neuroprotective actions of GLP-1RAs in animal models of 
123 
diabetes. Many of them have focused on the effects of GLP-1RAs on cerebral ischemia/reperfusion 
124 
injury. In diabetic rats with cerebral ischemia/reperfusion damage caused by middle cerebral artery 
125 
occlusion, recombinant GLP-1 improved neurological deficit and reduced cerebral infarct area, 
126 
mainly through the inhibition of oxidative stress and apoptosis (Fang et al., 2018). GLP-1RAs exert 
127 
favourable effects, such as the reduction of cognitive impairment induced by diabetes or obesity. 
128 
Indeed, it has been observed that peripheral administration of lixisenatide for 40 days (50 nmol/kg 
129 
bw, twice-daily) in high-fat fed mice with established obesity, insulin resistance and impaired 
130 
cognition resulted in marked improvement in recognition memory, which was associated with up-
131 
regulation of hippocampal expression of neurotrophic tyrosine kinase receptor type 2 and 
132 
mammalian target of rapamycin (mTOR) genes involved in modulating synaptic plasticity and long-
133 
term potentiation. Lixisenatide treatment promoted also hippocampal progenitor cells proliferation 
134 
and increased immature neurons in the hippocampal dentate gyrus (Lennox et al., 2014). Liraglutide 
135 
showed effects against hippocampal neurodegeneration induced by streptozotocin, an animal model 
136 
of diabetes and neurodegeneration associated with cognitive decline. In particular, liraglutide 
137 
improved learning and memory, and reduced hippocampal neuronal death (Palleria et al., 2017). In 
138 
addition, in a streptozotocin-induced mouse model of diabetes, pre-treatment with liraglutide 
139 
contrasted neuronal and synaptic damage in the hippocampal CA1 region (Kong et al., 2018).  
140 
Notably, neuroprotective activity of GLP-1RAs seem not to be entirely related to glycemia 
141 
normalization. Indeed, there is growing evidence about neuroprotective effects of GLP-1RAs in 
142 
animal models of neurodegenerative diseases, regardless of diabetes. Liraglutide reduced infarct 
143 
size in the brain of diabetic and non-diabetic rats but decreased neurologic deficits only in non-
144 
diabetic rats, suggesting that the GLP-1 RAs effects on cognitive function are not associated with 
145 
diabetes and glycemia normalization. Indeed, both liraglutide and metformin, a glucose lowering 
146 
agent acting via AMP-activated protein kinase-dependent pathways, induced euglycaemia in 
147 
diabetic rats, but only liraglutide treatment reduced ischemic brain damage (Filchenko et al., 2018).  
148 
 
149 
Provisional
4. 
GLP-1RAs as neuroprotective agents in neurodegenerative diseases  
150 
 
151 
Considering the beneficial effects of GLP-1RAs on neuropathological features it is conceivable a 
152 
link between T2D and neurodegenerative disease such as Parkinson disease (PD) and Alzheimer 
153 
Disease (AD). Neurodegenerative diseases have a considerable physical, psychological, social, and 
154 
economical impact, both on affected people and on their careers, families and society in general 
155 
(Whorld Healh Organization, 2017).  
156 
 
157 
4.1 Parkinson’s disease 
158 
 
159 
PD is a progressive nervous system disorder whose etiology remains still unclear, although genetic 
160 
and environmental factors seem to be involved. PD's clinical features include resting tremor, rigid 
161 
muscles, slowed movement (bradykinesia), postural instability and loss of purposeful movement 
162 
(Kalia and Lang, 2015). Pathological features are characterized by neurons impairment of substantia 
163 
nigra pars compacta with concomitant formation of intracellular Lewy bodies and loss of 
164 
dopaminergic neurons. Lewy bodies are abnormal aggregates of α-synuclein protein, which is 
165 
involved in dopamine (DA) metabolism and function. Dopaminergic neurons dysfunction and death 
166 
by apoptosis or autophagy are also associated with mitochondrial activity alteration, oxidative 
167 
stress, altered protein handling, and inflammatory condition (Olanow and Tatton, 1999). Rare 
168 
dominant form of PD in familial and sporadic cases are associated to point mutations, duplications 
169 
and triplications in the α-synuclein gene (Lesage and Brice, 2009). 
170 
In different preclinical models of PD, GLP-1RAs showed neuroprotective effects, influencing 
171 
motor activity, dopaminergic neurons, cortical activity and energy utilisation in the brain. Harkavyi 
172 
et al. tested the efficacy of exendin-4 in rat models of PD treated with 6-hydroxydopamine (6-
173 
OHDA) and lipopolysaccaride (LPS). They observed that in striatal tissue DA concentrations were 
174 
markedly higher in 6-OHDA/LPS + exendin-4 treated rats with respect to 6-OHDA/LPS + vehicle 
175 
groups. This effect was associated with an increase in the tyrosine hydroxylase enzyme involved in 
176 
the production of L-dopa, a DA precursor. In the same PD rat model exendin-4 was able to promote 
177 
adult neurogenesis in vitro e in vivo, normalizing dopamine imbalance, showing an increase in 
178 
tyrosine hydroxylase- and vesicular monoamine transporter 2-positive neurons in the substantia 
179 
nigra (Bertilsson et al., 2008). Other authors observed that the administration of exendin-4, 
180 
liraglutide and lixisenatide in the same mouse model prevented both motor dysfunction and tyrosine 
181 
hydroxylase levels reduction in the substantia nigra and basal ganglia. Furthermore, liraglutide and 
182 
lixisenatide induced a marked increase in anti-apoptotic pathways compared to exendin-4 (Liu et 
183 
al., 2015). 
184 
Recently, the long-term administration of liraglutide was found to rescue dopaminergic neuronal 
185 
loss and motor impairment also in diabetic db/db mice, an established model of diabetes, with a 
186 
mutation in the gene encoding the leptin receptor (Ma et al., 2019), suggesting that long-term 
187 
injection of liraglutide might prevent motor function impairment and PD development also in 
188 
patients with T2D. In rotenone-induced PD model, liraglutide together with sitagliptin, a DPP IV 
189 
inhibitor, increased striatal dopamine and tyrosine hydroxylase protein levels, reduced 
190 
neuroinflammation and reversed neuronal loss (Badawi et al., 2017). Liraglutide was also able to 
191 
attenuate dyskinesia, a serious complication of long term therapy with L-dopa (Badawi et al., 2019).  
192 
In the MPTP mouse model of PD, semaglutide improved most of neuropathological features of PD, 
193 
reversing motor impairment, inducing the increase of tyrosine hydroxylase levels, attenuating 
194 
neuroinflammation and apoptosis in the substantia nigra and striatum (Zhang et al., 2018). A 
195 
reduction in α-synuclein aggregation occurred after this treatment, not observed with other GLP-
196 
1RAs (Zhang et al., 2019), highlighting semaglutide as an effective treatment for PD. 
197 
Preliminary clinical studies were performed with subcutaneous injections of exenatide in PD 
198 
patients. Athauda et al. reported the results of the first randomized, double-blind, placebo-controlled 
199 
trial in 62 patients affected by moderate PD. Patients were randomly assigned to receive 
200 
Provisional
subcutaneous injections of exenatide 2 mg once-weekly (n.32) or placebo (n.30) for 48 weeks. 
201 
Exenatide had positive and sustained effects (12 weeks after exposure) on clinically assessed motor 
202 
function (Athauda et al., 2017). A post hoc analysis indicated that even non-motor symptoms, such 
203 
as clinically evaluated mood and emotional well-being, improved in patients treated with exenatide 
204 
although these beneficial effects did not last after interruption (Athauda et al., 2018). Patients 
205 
treated with exenatide had significantly higher tyrosine phosphorylation of insulin receptor 
206 
substrate 1 and higher expression of total Akt and phosphorylated mTOR than placebo-treated 
207 
patients providing a possible insulin-based molecular mechanism explanation for the results 
208 
observed in clinical trial (Athauda et al., 2019).  
209 
 
210 
4.2 
Alzheimer’s disease 
211 
 
212 
Dementia is a chronic disease, which affects memory, other cognitive abilities and behaviour. It is 
213 
estimated that approximately 50 million people worldwide have dementia. Currently, it is the 7th 
214 
leading cause of death and it is one of the major causes of disability worldwide. Pre-diabetic risk 
215 
factors, obesity and metabolic syndrome can promote cognitive dysfunction. AD is the most 
216 
common form of dementia, contributing to 60–70% of cases. The main neuropathological features 
217 
of AD are neurofibrillary tangles, formed by hyperphosphorylated tau proteins, which aggregate 
218 
into oligomers, and the amyloid plaques, formed by aggregated β-amyloid peptides (Aβ)  (Calsolaro 
219 
and Edison, 2015).  
220 
Increasing evidence suggests a link between T2D and AD. In particular, these conditions might 
221 
share defects in insulin signaling. Interestingly, in a mouse model of genetically induced AD-like 
222 
neuropathology (3xTg-AD mice) peripheral glucose intolerance was observed. Treatment with 
223 
pioglitazone, a glucose lowering drug, greatly improved cognitive impairment of these mice 
224 
confirming the neurotrophic role of insulin (Masciopinto et al., 2012). In the same model, high-fat 
225 
diet further potentiated glucose intolerance and enhanced neuropathological features of AD and 
226 
memory deficits. Insulin adoption reversed the negative effect of high-fat diet, interrupting the 
227 
vicious cycle between diabetes and AD (Vandal et al., 2014). Both studies highlighted the 
228 
neurotrophic role of insulin in brain. 
229 
Conversely, hyperinsulinemia induced by peripheral administration of insulin increased tau 
230 
phosphorylation by in C57BL/6 mice (Freude et al., 2005).  
231 
Aβ oligomers induced reduction of Insulin Receptors (IRs) activity due to the phosphorylation of 
232 
IRS-1 at serine residues (IRS-1pSer), with a consequent loss of substrate affinity as observed in 
233 
T2D. As reported by Bomfim at al., in the mouse hippocampal neurons Aβ oligomers are also 
234 
thought to activate the TNF-α/JNK signaling, inducing insulin resistance (Bomfim et al., 2012; De 
235 
Felice, 2013). The GLP-1RAs not only prevents JNK/IKK activation, but promotes insulin 
236 
activation by PI3K/AKT axis, with the subsequently activation of mTOR and the block of GSK-3β, 
237 
an essential kinase also involved for the phosphorylation of tau protein (Moloney et al., 2010). Ma 
238 
et al. reported that liraglutide administration prevented tau hyperphosphorylation associated with 
239 
aging in diabetic db/db mouse (Ma et al., 2015). 
240 
The role of vascular dysfunction has recently emerged as significant contributor in the 
241 
pathophysiology of AD. Blood-brain barrier and cerebral blood flow reduction might precede Aβ 
242 
oligomers and tau deposition and it is associated to cognitive decline (Hachinski et al., 2019; Nation 
243 
et al., 2019). In APP/PS1 transgenic mice liraglutide reduced the incidence of cerebral 
244 
microanuerysms and leakage (Kelly et al., 2015).  
245 
GLP-1RAs have shown neuroprotective effects in several preclinical studies in AD. Notably, they 
246 
seem to improve nearly all neuropathological features in AD and cognitive functions as well. In 12-
247 
month-old female APP/PS1/tau AD mouse model, neurofibrillary tangles, amyloid plaques and 
248 
neuroinflammation in the hippocampi have been reduced by lixisenatide (Cai et al., 2018). In the rat 
249 
model, lixisenatide also prevented synaptic damage induced by Aβ accumulation and strengthened 
250 
spatial memory by affecting the PI3K-Akt-GSK3β (Cai et al., 2014). The GLP-1RA exenatide (20 
251 
Provisional
µgr/kg/day, intraperitoneally for two weeks) reduced neuroinflammation by suppressing the TNF-α 
252 
levels in rats. Furthermore, it improved memory and prevented the loss of hippocampal neurons 
253 
(Solmaz et al., 2015). 
254 
Recently, it has been observed that 4-week-treatment with exendin-4 reversed memory impairment 
255 
in APP/PS1 mice, downregulating the aberrant N-acetylglucosaminyltransferase III expression 
256 
through the Akt/GSK-3β/β-catenin signaling pathway in neurons. N-acetylglucosamine levels 
257 
seems to be increased in the cerebrospinal fluid of most AD patients, and the levels of N-
258 
acetylglucosaminyltransferase III, a glycosyltransferase responsible for synthesizing a bisecting 
259 
GlcNAc residue, were found to be highly expressed in the brains of AD patients as well (Wang et 
260 
al., 2018).  
261 
Liraglutide (25nmol/kg, intraperitoneally, for 2 months) improved spatial memory in 14-month-old 
262 
APP/PS1 mouse model, compared to saline-treated mice. It also reduced inflammation and plaque 
263 
load, while neuronal progenitor cell in the dentate gyrus increased. Long term potentiation was 
264 
significantly enhanced as well and synapse numbers increased in the hippocampus and cortex 
265 
(McClean and Holscher, 2014). In another study, the same authors observed that liraglutide might 
266 
also protect from progressive neurodegeneration that develops in AD: in 2-month old mice, 
267 
liraglutide (once-daily intraperitoneally for 8 months) contrasted synaptic damage and improved 
268 
memory. In addition, amyloid plaque load was reduced, inflammation was reduced in the cortex, 
269 
and neurogenesis was enhanced in the dentate gyrus (McClean et al., 2015). On the contrary, other 
270 
authors did not report beneficial effects of liraglutide on cerebral plaque load, in APP/PS1 
271 
transgenic mouse models of AD with two different clinical APP/PS1 mutations (Hansen et al., 
272 
2016). In the mouse model, memory deficit was improved by subcutaneous administration of 
273 
liraglutide (25 nmol/day once daily for 8 week), decreasing the phosphorylation of tau (Qi et al., 
274 
2016). 
275 
Furthermore, in APP/PS-1 mice at different ages, chronic administration of liraglutide promoted 
276 
neural progenitor cells proliferation. Both acute and chronic treatment increased the number of 
277 
immature neurons in animals at all ages, and the differentiation into mature neurons was observed 
278 
for most immature cells (Parthsarathy and Holscher, 2013).  
279 
Even in a mouse model of pathological aging, which shares neurobehavioral and neuropathological 
280 
dysfunction with sporadic AD at an early phase, liraglutide increased the number of CA1 pyramidal 
281 
neuron in hippocampus and improved memory (Hansen et al., 2015). 
282 
The effects of GLP-1RAs on synaptic protection might involve the modulation of the brain-derived 
283 
neurotrophic factor (BDNF), a trophic factor which promotes neural progenitor cell differentiation 
284 
and survival. Indeed, exenatide activates the transcription factor CREB with an increase of BDNF 
285 
protein expression promoting the activation of neurotrophic pathway and inhibiting apoptosis in a 
286 
mouse model of age-dependent cognitive dysfunction, potentiating long term memory (Bomba et 
287 
al., 2018). Even in a mouse model of AD (the 3xTg-AD undergoing high fat diet), exenatide 
288 
reverted the impairment of BDNF signaling and neuroinflammation (Bomba et al., 2019). 
289 
In the last few years, even dual and triple receptor agonists have been developed, with remarkable 
290 
results in animal models. Indeed, GLP-1/Gastric Inhibitory Polypeptide (GIP) dual agonist DA5-
291 
CH strengthened working memory and long term spatial memory in APP/PS1 transgenic AD mouse 
292 
model (9- month-old). It also led to a reduction in hippocampal amyloid senile plaques and in 
293 
phosphorylated tau protein. The deficits in hippocampal late-phase long-term potentiation were 
294 
reversed and p-PI3K and p-AKT growth factor kinases were up regulated. The excessive activation 
295 
of p-GSKβ was prevented in the hippocampus (Cai et al., 2018). Promising results have been 
296 
observed with the dual GLP-1/GIP receptor agonist DA-JC4 as well, which decreased 
297 
phosphorylated tau levels in the rat cerebral cortex and hippocampus, prevented spatial learning 
298 
dysfunction, attenuated chronic inflammation response in the brain, reduced apoptosis and 
299 
reactivated insulin signaling pathways in streptozotocin (STZ)-induced AD rat model (Shi et al., 
300 
2017). Recently, a triple receptor agonist, activating GLP-1, GIP and glucagon receptors, rescued 
301 
memory dysfunction, showed anti-apoptotic effects, enhanced synaptophysin, protected from 
302 
Provisional
synaptic loss, reduced the total amount of Aβ, and reduced neuroinflammation (activated microglia 
303 
and astrocytes) and oxidative stress in the cortex and hippocampus (Tai et al., 2018). 
304 
Despite the large amount of evidence about the neuroprotective effects of GLP-1RAs in animal 
305 
models of AD, human studies are still scant. In a randomized, controlled, double-blind intervention 
306 
study in AD patients, no effect on the deposition of Aβ was observed in patients treated for six 
307 
months with liraglutide, compared to placebo (Egefjord et al., 2012). In a more recent 26-week, 
308 
double-blind RCT, although glucose metabolism increased in multiple regions in patients with AD 
309 
treated with liraglutide compared to placebo, the statistical power of the study was insufficient to 
310 
reach a conclusion about Aβ load and cognition measures (Gejl et al., 2016).  
311 
 
312 
5. 
Conclusions 
313 
 
314 
Overall, the results on the effects of GLP-1RAs in animal models of neurodegenerative diseases are 
315 
encouraging. However, further clinical research is needed to clarify whether they might be potential 
316 
agents for the treatment of PD and AD and other forms of cognitive impairment.  
317 
 
318 
6. 
Conflict of Interest 
319 
 
320 
The authors declare that this review was written in the absence of any commercial or financial 
321 
relationships that could be construed as a potential conflict of interest. 
322 
 
323 
7. 
Author Contributions 
324 
 
325 
MD and SM conceptualized and critically revised. TF, MG and MCG performed the PubMed 
326 
search and wrote the mini-review. BM and AG critically revised the article for intellectual content. 
327 
  
328 
8. 
Contribution to the Field Statement 
329 
 
330 
This mini-review summarizes many recent findings on the effect of the glucose-lowering drugs 
331 
GLP-1RAs on neurodegenerative diseases outcomes and features, and gives an overview of the 
332 
main pathophysiological mechanisms involved. 
333 
 
